.","Altered form of German   Weimer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wimer","meanings":["Altered form of English   Wymer   or German   Weimer  ."]},{"name":"Wymore","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Wymer  .","Altered form of German   Weimar  ."]},{"name":"Waymack","meanings":["Probably English: variant of <b>Waymark</b>, from the Old Breton personal name <i>Wiuhomarch</i> (modern <i>Guyonvarc'h</i>), Gallicized as Old French <i>Wimarc</i>, and brought to England with the Norman Conquest. The name is composed of Old Breton <i>uuiu</i> ‘worthy of’ + the prefix <i>ho-</i> ‘successfully’ + <i>march</i> ‘horse’. The personal name was used for women as well as men. See also   Wymer  , with which this name may have been confused in Anglo-Norman England."]},{"name":"Wimmer","meanings":["German: shortened form of   Widmer  .","German: occupational name from Middle High German <i>wimmer</i> ‘wine maker’.","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>wim(m)er</i> ‘knotty growth on a tree trunk’."]}]},{"name":"Gundred","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Gundry  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gundry","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from <i>Gondri</i>, <i>Gundric</i>, an Old French personal name introduced to Britain by the Normans, composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gund</i> ‘battle’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":28,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Gundred Wyger was born in 1354, in Thorverton, 